## OIS Engagement — Full Correspondence Timeline

### Phase 1: Application & Sketch (Aug 4–23, 2025)

**Aug 4** — Marwan applies via email.
Shares ArtStation portfolio + 7 samples.
Highlights love for storytelling/atmosphere,
references hexagonal visual theme from Evan's brief.

**Aug 6** — Evan advances Marwan to next round.

**Aug 7** — Evan sends creative direction document,
commissions a sketch.

**Aug 8** — First payment.
Sketch at $250 ($125 upfront, $125 on approval).
Solana crypto — Marwan prefers crypto over PayPal/bank.
Evan accidentally sends SOL instead of USDC;
Marwan is gracious about the mix-up.
He'll do a normal art draft first, then convert to pixel art.
Canvas: 1920×1080.

**Aug 10** — Marwan delivers first draft sketch within 2 days.
Full composition showing where each element sits.

**Aug 12** — Evan sends extensive organized feedback:

- Room size: cozy
- Ducks: inside window, furry not feathered, purple bills, one with personality
- Chandelier: hexagonal, six candles
- Outdoor lights: interesting, keep
- Holdt: key to scene, dodecahedron necklace
- Music box: hexagonal/steampunk, speaker horn, wind-up key
- Picture of Phoebe and Hodlen: hexagon frame, child-drawn
- Hexagonal pixel concept: attached examples

Asks for animation pricing and next steps.

**Aug 12** — Marwan responds point by point.
On hex pixels: no software draws hexagons natively,
could convert after but warns it may look blurry.
Recommends standard pixels.
On animation: lists scope items
(rain w/ collision, duck breathing, Holdt,
candle flicker, music box, decorations)
but can't quote yet.

**Aug 13** — Evan agrees to normal pixels
with hex review at end. Start small on animation.

**Aug 16** — Marwan delivers 3 sketch versions:
one clean with changes,
two with lighting/shading showing atmosphere options
including a steampunk/sci-fi variant.

**Aug 19** — Evan responds after wedding/holiday delay.
Requests wider hexagon window (1.5x top/bottom edges),
plants around exterior, side hexagons as windows.
Marwan agrees on plants,
pushes back on side windows (would pull focus),
offers compromise: glass reflections that read as windows
without showing interior.

**Aug 20** — Marwan delivers updated sketch:
wider window, indoor plants, cacti on windowsill.
Multiple rounds on window cutoff, plant placement,
duck furriness, lighting position
(Evan wants slightly left of center, LoFi Girl reference).

**Aug 22** — Marwan delivers version with outdoor plants
and fully uncut window.
Explains original cutoff was for geometric evenness
but defers to Evan.

**Aug 23** — Sketch approved.
Illustration pricing negotiated.
Evan proposes $250 illustration + $500 animation.
Marwan counters: $650 illustration (citing detail level),
~$550 animation estimate.
Evan agrees to $650 despite being over budget,
citing partnership strength and talent recognition.
Sends first half ($325).
Business email switches to innkeep@outsideinn.tv.

### Phase 2: Illustration & Financial Formalization (Oct–Dec 2025)

**Oct 20** — Dedicated "Pixel Art Financials" thread opened.
Marwan quotes $220 for major changes.
Evan had already sent $200 (Marwan hadn't noticed),
net owed $20.

**Oct 20** — NDA negotiated and signed same day.
Marwan requests two additions:
credit rights wherever credits are customarily displayed,
and portfolio rights post-public release
(permission required only if unreleased).
Evan incorporates both immediately.
Marwan signs and returns same day.

**Nov 5** — After an inspiring video call,
Marwan quotes $250 for new major changes.
Evan pays Nov 6.

**Dec 12** — $120 for outside sketch/design changes.
Paid same day.

**Dec 19** — Evan sends $50 unprompted holiday bonus.
Warm exchange — mutual respect and excitement.

**Dec 30–31** — Logo/wordmark negotiated.
Two options: cheaper vs. expensive with multiple concepts.
Evan chooses expensive option.
Marwan quotes $550,
voluntarily drops to $500
("I'll make it a lifetime logo for you").
Evan sends first half ($250) Dec 31.

### Phase 3: Illustration Completion & Animation Start (Jan 2026)

**Jan 11** — Illustration complete.
Marwan requests remaining $325.

**Jan 12** — Evan pays $325.
Sets expectation for animation:
upfront total cost with defined revision rounds.
Notes illustration scope crept multiple times
(acknowledges all charges were fair).
Marwan clarifies extras came from
scope changes Evan initiated.
Asks if Evan has a budget in mind.

**Jan 12 (later)** — Marwan proposes percentage revenue share
in exchange for reduced animation cost.
Evan declines clearly:
percentage revenue requires recurring value production,
current partnership is project-based.
Offers milestone-based poster bonus
and NFT allocation (1 of 6 Gold NFTs).

**Jan 13** — Marwan accepts gracefully,
calls terms fair,
expresses enthusiasm about NFT opportunity.

**Jan 16** — Animation payment part 1 ($500) sent.
Brief payment friction:
Evan out of SOL, can't send ETH,
Marwan doesn't use PayPal,
Wise unavailable to Evan.
They stick with SOL; Evan buys more, sends same day.

### Phase 4: Contract Negotiation (Feb 2026)

**Feb 24** — Evan sends comprehensive draft contract
covering all past payments, remaining deliverables,
and royalty structure.

**Feb 24 (same day)** — Marwan responds with
3 revision requests and 3 clarifying questions:

Revisions:
1. Defined acceptance/review timeframe
2. Animation polish capped at 3 rounds, extras billed separately
3. Royalties: proposes 8% net sales, raise/remove cap, auto-apply to all merch, quarterly payouts

Questions:
1. Is remaining $250 from logo budget now Holdt portrait?
2. What exactly does "animation polish" entail?
3. Did they agree on $150 for stream alerts? Can't find it in writing.

**Feb 25** — Evan responds point by point:

**Accepted:**
- 7 business day review window (deemed accepted if no response)
- Payment within 5 business days of acceptance
- Polish capped at 3 rounds (new scenes/structural changes excluded)
- Royalty auto-applies to all merch with his art
- Quarterly payouts with sales summary
- Payout threshold $497.70
- Royalty term extended from 7 to 14 years

**Declined:**
- 8% net sales royalty — stays with $0.77 flat per unit

**Compromised:**
- Lifetime cap raised to $7,700 ($770 × 10)

**Answers:**
- Yes, $250 goes to Holdt portrait
- Polish = color adjustments, timing tweaks, smoothness, small fixes
- $150 for alerts was likely verbal; Evan stands behind it

**Added:**
- Artist signature on merch
- Source file delivery required
- Originality warranty + IP indemnification
- Independent contractor clause
- Binding arbitration with 2-year lookback
- Backup IP assignment clause

Evan signs revised contract, sends via DocuSign.

### Phase 5: Final Delivery & Launch (Feb 27 – Mar 3, 2026)

**Feb 27** — Evan checks in.
Marwan says focused on exporting animation,
everything ready by Sunday max.
Will address contract once animation is done.
Asks if Evan only needs raw panel files.
Evan clarifies: not good at editing,
good with technology —
give isolated animation files, he'll handle sound sync.

**Mar 1** — Marwan delivers 480 PNG frames
of Holdt animation plus panel files via Google Drive.
Says "it was great working with you on this
and it was a nice journey."
This is what Evan turned into HoldtLoop.mp4
(1h40m, 1920×1080, H.264+AAC, ~1.28GB)
using DaVinci Resolve + FFmpeg before Broadcast Alpha.

**Mar 2** — Evan asks for a call before launch.
No confirmed call in writing.

**Mar 3 (Broadcast Alpha)** — Marwan follows up
asking if files were received.
No reply from Evan visible
(likely occupied with first stream).
The animation ran 11h39m without a single drop.
Marwan's work is now live on YouTube and Twitch.

### The Luiz Pixel Art Experiment

Evan asked Marwan to touch up / convert
Luiz's illustration work into pixel art.
It didn't work — the styles didn't translate.
Marwan was a great sport about it.
No friction, no ego, no lingering tension.
Evidence of flexibility and professionalism
when experiments don't pan out.

